<Javalab>
  <config><![CDATA[{
  "game_id": 68,
  "created_at": "2025-03-13T00:07:15.000Z",
  "level_num": "custom",
  "user_id": 16889,
  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "The <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">TrafficPainter</code> class declares instance variables for a 1D array of <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">String</code> values that stores the paint colors a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">TrafficPainter</code> object can paint with.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">TrafficPainter.java</code>, write the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">shiftColors()</code> method to adjust the order of paint colors before navigating traffic.\r\n\r\nThe <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">shiftColors()</code> method should:\r\n\r\n1. Take an integer parameter that represents how many positions to shift.\r\n\r\n2. Loop for the number of shifts requested.\r\n\r\n3. For each shift:\r\n\t\r\n    - Store the first color in the 1D array <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">paintColors</code> in a temporary variable.\r\n    \r\n    - Loop through the array (except for the last element), shifting each color one position to the left.\r\n    \r\n    - Move the original first color to the last position in the array.\r\n\r\n4. Return the modified array so it can be used in <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">navigateTraffic()</code>.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">NeighborhoodRunner.java</code>:\r\n\r\n1. Instantiate a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">TrafficPainter</code> object at <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">(0, 13)</code> facing <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">\"North\"</code> with <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">50</code> units of paint.\r\n\r\n2. Declare and initialize a 1D array to store three paint colors.\r\n\r\n3. Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">shiftColors()</code> method before calling <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">navigateTraffic()</code>.\r\n\r\n4. Pass the modified array to <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">navigateTraffic()</code>.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the <strong>Help & Tips</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with traversing a 1D array with a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">for</code> loop.\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<details style=\"background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;\">\r\n    <summary style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;\">🔦 Need help with your algorithm?</summary>\r\n    <div style=\"margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;\">\r\n    \t<p>Here is one approach to solving this problem.</p>\r\n        <pre style=\"background-color: #333333; color: white;\">\r\nfor shift number times\r\n  temp = paintColors[0]\r\n  for each value in paintColors\r\n  \tpaintColors[index] = paintColors[index + 1]\r\n  paintColors[paintColors.length - 1] = temp  \r\n</pre>\r\n    </div>\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## ***Don't forget to . . .***\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/eb2c8910ae2e150019b8e2177405d4af-image-1668191576873.png)\r\n\r\n## 🎯 Goal\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/b5a44fe6d176edebaa876da660d6565b-image-1648557517951.gif)",
    "mini_rubric": "false",
